    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-12-06T17:45:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-12-06T17:45:00-05:00" n="441"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d441">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">856D.2553/12–651: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Embassy in Indonesia</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-12-06T17:45:00-05:00"
                            >December 6, 1951—5:45 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>597. Ernst, asst to Board Chairman <gloss target="#t_Caltex1">Caltex</gloss>,
                    called on Lacy yesterday to discuss <gloss target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss> Govt
                    attitude on revision its “let alone” fon exchange control agreements with oil
                    cos. Though <gloss target="#t_Caltex1">Caltex</gloss> Agreement does not expire
                    until Jan 1, 1953, Ernst stated his co very disturbed by reports from <gloss
                        target="#t_Stanvac1">Stanvac</gloss>, NY, on its negots related to
                    expiration latter’s agreement Dec 31 this year. Ernst said he understood <gloss
                        target="#t_Stanvac1">Stanvac</gloss> negotiators departing NY had been given
                    Dec 15 “arrival deadline” by Kuypers. Ernst attributed to Kuypers preponderant
                    responsibility for <gloss target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss> Govt’s actions contrary
                    to oil cos interests, and had intended send special <gloss target="#t_Caltex1"
                        >Caltex</gloss> negotiator to “go over Kuypers head” to higher level <gloss
                        target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss> officials.</p>
                <p>Lacy informed Ernst that Amer Amb has returned Djakarta, is closely fol
                    developments affecting oil cos, and is in touch with high level <gloss
                        target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss> officials on this matter. Lacy added recent
                    report from Emb (<gloss target="#t_urtel1">urtel</gloss> 798 Dec 3)<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d441fn1">Not here printed.</note> indicate <gloss target="#t_Indo1"
                        >Indo</gloss>s in negotiating frame of mind. It was pointed out Butterworth
                    of <gloss target="#t_Caltex1">Caltex</gloss> is now in <gloss target="#t_Indo1"
                        >Indo</gloss> and that it wld probably be advisable <gloss
                        target="#t_Caltex1">Caltex</gloss> refrain from sending special mission to
                    Djakarta this time, in order avoid appearance of “US oil cos ganging up” on
                        <gloss target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss>s. Ernst stated he was reassured to
                    learn Amb Cochran has returned Djakarta, and that <gloss target="#t_Indo1"
                        >Indo</gloss> Govt appears to be acting reasonably. He will communicate with
                    Butterworth before recommending <gloss target="#t_Caltex1">Caltex</gloss> send
                    any special mission.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Webb</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
